I laugh when people call $AMZN overvalued.

It runs the most advanced logistics network in the world, owns the strongest point-of-purchase ad business in the consumer economy & AWS now generates more profit than the entire retail arm.

And it still trades cheaper than $WMT & $COST.

Why is $ORCL down 30% in the past month? 

Because Oracle is taking on the most aggressive capex plan in the industry & funding a data center buildout that is outsized relative to its revenue base.

When you tie ~$500B of future obligations to one counterparty in OpenAI then the market starts assigning a Sam Altman risk premium.

The upside is very real if demand holds & if Oracle can deploy capacity faster than $AMZN, $MSFT or $GOOGL but the balance-sheet and concentration risks are just as real.

I think the payoff will be enormous.

This chart shows the real state of AI.

‚Ä¢ Capex is tracking toward $600B 2028 which means $AMZN, $MSFT, $GOOGL, $META & $ORCL are now building some of the largest industrial projects ever attempted.
‚Ä¢ The real constraint is shifting from GPU supply to power + land because every new model cycle adds another wave of megawatt demand.
‚Ä¢ This spending will not normalize since a multi-gigawatt footprint needs to be refreshed every 3-4 years.

Whoever secures power and land & can stand up capacity the fastest will end up owning the AI economy of the next decade.

$GOOGL is basically saying the long-term bottleneck for AI is power. 

If TPUs can operate in space where solar is 8x stronger then power stops being the constraint & the cost curve for compute opens up in a meaningful way.

The 50-year mortgage idea is an acknowledgement that home prices are unaffordable. Instead of lowering home prices through more supply (new construction) and hurting homeowners‚Äô ability to retire, we‚Äôre floating the idea of returning to innovative mortgage finance to try to make it work.

If this is the road we are going down, how will this not end badly like the last time?

The Mag 7 combined account for almost 35% of the S&P 500, with Nvidia $NVDA, Apple $AAPL and Microsoft $MSFT alone accounting for more than one-fifth of the index with a combined weighting of 19.7%.

HSBC estimates that OpenAI could need $207 billion in financing by 2030 to meet all of its compute capacity commitments, adding that capital injections, debt or higher revenue than modeled could close the funding gap.

$MSFT $ORCL $AMD $AVGO $NVDA

BofA's Vivek Arya expects the AI data center TAM to grow ~5X to roughly $1.2T by 2030, up from $242B this year. 

Nvidia $NVDA is "still expected to dominate the market, though it may only have a 75% market share, down from the estimated 85% it currently holds, Arya explained."

Since September, Amazon $AMZN, Alphabet $GOOG, Oracle $ORCL and Meta $META have issued around $90 billion in investment grade bonds, more than they have sold over the last 40 months, per Dealogic, likely to help fund rising AI investments.

About 9 months ago, the market thought $GOOGL was toast bc Chat-GPT's success was going to threaten search (where Google clearly owns the market).

Now, the market has not only reversed it's "feelings" on Google but grown quite ambitious - as just today - the market thinks $GOOGL is so strong it can overtake $NVDA on custom silicon (where Nvidia clearly owns the market with GPUs). Nevermind that TPUs have been around for nearly a decade.

Crazy how market sentiment works, huh?

Those calling this an ‚ÄúAI bubble‚Äù assume monetization efforts will not offset the capital being invested. 

What if the opposite happens after the initial monetization gap - revenue accelerates, profits begin to scale, and the market reprices AI companies dramatically higher. 

I shared my thoughts last week in my interview with @cvpayne on why the biggest risk to investors is not that AI is in a bubble - but rather the opportunity cost of missing out.
